      "lineNbr": 25,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001993
      },
      "writtenOn": "2026-03-04T12:27:30Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Yes, using `sd_notify()` or a `D-Bus` method would allow implementing reload in a synchronous manner. However, at present, I couldn’t find any use case that requires synchronous reload .\n\nRegarding `sd_notify()`, adopting it would require changing the service from `Type\u003ddbus` to either `Type\u003dnotify or Type\u003dnotify-reload`, since systemd does not support multiple Type\u003d modes. Switching away from the current type Type\u003ddbus would alter how readiness is tracked. Currently, systemd considers the service ready once the D-Bus name is acquired. With `Type\u003dnotify/Type\u003dnotify-reload`, we would need to explicitly send `sd_notify(\"READY\u003d1\")` after acquiring the D-Bus name.Also, Type\u003ddbus implicitly manages D-Bus-related ordering and dependencies. Moving away from it would require explicitly specifying those dependencies in the service file.\n\nAnd regarding `D-Bus-based mechanism`, we currently do not have an PDI to implement reload mechanism and hence I had proposed a PDI for the same sometime back and the feedback was since no synchronous reload is required, and systemd-based signaling satisfies the current need, using a signal-based reload is simple and sufficient. Attaching reference for the PDI patch : https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/phosphor-dbus-interfaces/+/83048\n\nBased on these considerations, the SIGHUP based approach was chosen.",
      "parentUuid": "5ea68411_6503d32f",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 24,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 25,
        "endChar": 28
      },
      "revId": "595c21ddcf1047b96f196e6de5d1b25e27879a15",
      "serverId": "adbd0a64-1f21-4d83-b585-671fe73cb6e4"
    },
